1
00:00:32,907 --> 00:00:36,119
ALL CHARACTERS, ORGANIZATIONS, PLACES, AND
ASSOCIATIONS IN THIS DRAMA ARE FICTITIOUS

2
00:00:36,202 --> 00:00:37,996
NEW BEGINNING OF LIFE!
IT IS UP TO YOUR MINDSET

3
00:00:45,712 --> 00:00:46,546
Sir.

4
00:00:50,717 --> 00:00:53,970
To a patient, an illness is despair,
and a doctor is hope.

5
00:00:54,679 --> 00:00:57,182
That hope. Will you let him down?

6
00:01:01,269 --> 00:01:02,312
What must I do…

7
00:01:03,855 --> 00:01:05,690
-to save him?
-First of all,

8
00:01:07,108 --> 00:01:08,568
tie your shoes.

9
00:01:11,321 --> 00:01:12,697
And then…

10
00:01:13,823 --> 00:01:15,366
follow the patient to the hospital.

11
00:01:15,450 --> 00:01:16,785
That's the first step.

12
00:01:17,368 --> 00:01:20,205
AMBULANCE

13
00:01:20,288 --> 00:01:24,375
EMERGENCY ROOM

14
00:01:35,804 --> 00:01:37,514
Blood pressure, 130 over 90,
heart rate, 50.

15
00:01:37,597 --> 00:01:40,558
In a mental stupor.
Spontaneous but irregular breathing.

16
00:01:41,643 --> 00:01:43,478
I guess we're in the same boat.

17
00:01:43,561 --> 00:01:46,523
Check his vitals. Hook him up to an IV
and give him normal saline.

18
00:01:46,606 --> 00:01:47,482
-Yes.
-Come here.

19
00:01:48,525 --> 00:01:49,359
Doctor.

20
00:01:50,610 --> 00:01:51,486
His kidneys.

21
00:01:53,238 --> 00:01:55,448
Check his kidneys first.

22
00:02:08,753 --> 00:02:10,004
Here is your coffee, sir.

23
00:02:13,842 --> 00:02:17,011
What happened?
What is wrong with Inmate 5353?

24
00:02:17,095 --> 00:02:18,555
Will he live?

25
00:02:19,222 --> 00:02:21,307
-I don't know.
-What?

26
00:02:24,018 --> 00:02:26,354
Whether he lives or dies
isn't up to me now.

27
00:02:28,106 --> 00:02:29,858
It's up to Dr. Kang.

28
00:02:31,192 --> 00:02:32,443
Si-young?

29
00:02:35,488 --> 00:02:36,406
You don't know?

30
00:02:37,240 --> 00:02:40,869
If you don't know what the problem is,
why did you tell me to check his kidneys?

31
00:02:42,162 --> 00:02:43,788
-Well…
-Hold on.

32
00:02:44,789 --> 00:02:45,665
No way.

33
00:02:47,125 --> 00:02:48,835
-Don't tell me it's him.
-Pardon?

34
00:02:48,918 --> 00:02:51,087
He didn't tell you to do this, did he?

35
00:02:51,170 --> 00:02:53,006
Inmate 6238 at Chungil Penitentiary.

36
00:02:53,631 --> 00:02:54,465
Do you know him?

37
00:02:57,886 --> 00:02:59,929
-Are you crazy?
-What?

38
00:03:00,013 --> 00:03:01,097
Did you give me an order

39
00:03:01,180 --> 00:03:03,474
based on the opinion
of a disqualified doctor in prison?

40
00:03:03,558 --> 00:03:06,686
-Well, the thing is--
-Did he say the patient was going to die?

41
00:03:09,147 --> 00:03:10,189
Every single time.

42
00:03:11,149 --> 00:03:14,152
I don't know what he told you,
but you shouldn't trust him.

43
00:03:15,111 --> 00:03:18,114
-What is this all about?
-Doctor, the result is out.

44
00:03:25,455 --> 00:03:26,581
RENAL FUNCTION TEST

45
00:03:44,140 --> 00:03:45,558
Did he name a disease too?

46
00:03:46,768 --> 00:03:48,061
What was he suspecting?

47
00:03:48,144 --> 00:03:49,062
What's going on?

48
00:03:50,647 --> 00:03:52,607
His BUN and creatinine levels
are elevated.

49
00:03:52,690 --> 00:03:55,026
The urinalysis for protein
turned out positive.

50
00:03:56,110 --> 00:03:58,488
In any case, it was a good call
to check his kidneys.

51
00:03:59,197 --> 00:04:01,032
So, what's his diagnosis?

52
00:04:05,787 --> 00:04:06,913
UNCLE JEONG-NAM

53
00:04:07,872 --> 00:04:09,165
Excuse me for a second.

54
00:04:12,794 --> 00:04:13,878
Uncle.

55
00:04:13,962 --> 00:04:15,380
Did they check his kidneys?

56
00:04:15,964 --> 00:04:17,340
Yes, they did.

57
00:04:17,423 --> 00:04:20,468
-What's the result?
-Positive for protein in the urine.

58
00:04:20,551 --> 00:04:22,345
All right. Start a kidney biopsy.

59
00:04:23,263 --> 00:04:24,222
A kidney biopsy?

60
00:04:25,807 --> 00:04:27,558
Start right away. There's no time to lose.

61
00:04:27,642 --> 00:04:28,935
Hold on.

62
00:04:29,894 --> 00:04:30,812
Yes?

63
00:04:30,895 --> 00:04:32,605
What's the disease you have in mind?

64
00:04:33,773 --> 00:04:35,233
I don't think you'll believe me.

65
00:04:36,484 --> 00:04:37,902
One out of 117,000.

66
00:04:37,986 --> 00:04:40,405
There's only
a 0.00001 percent probability.

67
00:04:41,239 --> 00:04:43,449
-What?
-In other words,

68
00:04:43,533 --> 00:04:46,911
because of
that 0.00001 percent probability,

69
00:04:46,995 --> 00:04:48,538
the patient might die.

70
00:04:48,621 --> 00:04:49,622
So?

71
00:04:49,706 --> 00:04:51,958
What's the name of the disease?

72
00:04:53,001 --> 00:04:55,712
Angiokeratoma gives him
burning pains in his limbs.

73
00:04:58,881 --> 00:05:00,758
Corneal clouding
irrespective of his sight.

74
00:05:01,884 --> 00:05:02,927
He's not sweating at all.

75
00:05:03,011 --> 00:05:05,179
Anhidrosis stops his sweating completely.

76
00:05:06,222 --> 00:05:09,976
TIAs, which mean
transient ischemic attacks.

77
00:05:11,185 --> 00:05:14,981
In addition, he's been experiencing
diarrhea, vomiting, and stomachache.

78
00:05:15,815 --> 00:05:17,108
Therefore, the diagnosis is…

79
00:05:17,734 --> 00:05:19,110
-Fabry disease.
-Fabry disease.

80
00:05:29,162 --> 00:05:31,539
EMERGENCY ROOM

81
00:05:32,081 --> 00:05:32,915
Fabry disease?

82
00:05:33,458 --> 00:05:35,752
Which affects only 100 people
in the whole country?

83
00:05:35,835 --> 00:05:38,671
Do you want to do a kidney biopsy
relying on that slim chance?

84
00:05:38,755 --> 00:05:40,757
Still, all the symptoms are right.

85
00:05:40,840 --> 00:05:44,135
Also, even though the chance is slim,
it also means

86
00:05:44,218 --> 00:05:48,264
that the patient might die because
of that 0.00001 percent probability.

87
00:05:48,765 --> 00:05:50,308
Fabry disease is hard to diagnose.

88
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:53,978
Also, that disease requires
enzymatic therapy.

89
00:05:54,062 --> 00:05:56,314
-The medication is hard to come by.
-So?

90
00:05:56,397 --> 00:05:58,024
Are you not even going to check for it?

91
00:05:59,358 --> 00:06:01,360
What if it really is Fabry disease?

92
00:06:04,238 --> 00:06:06,365
Then check his family history first.

93
00:06:06,449 --> 00:06:10,661
Someone else might have it
as it's a genetic disorder?

94
00:06:10,745 --> 00:06:11,788
What's your department?

95
00:06:12,830 --> 00:06:14,082
Anesthesiology.

96
00:06:14,165 --> 00:06:15,583
Same here. Which year?

97
00:06:15,666 --> 00:06:17,043
Second…

98
00:06:19,253 --> 00:06:20,463
year.

99
00:06:20,546 --> 00:06:21,964
You can relax.

100
00:06:22,048 --> 00:06:24,675
I'm just a fellow
who is on duty all the time.

101
00:06:25,426 --> 00:06:26,928
What's wrong with being a fellow?

102
00:06:29,097 --> 00:06:30,306
Si-young.

103
00:06:30,848 --> 00:06:31,766
Just a second.

104
00:06:31,849 --> 00:06:33,935
-Find out his family history.
-Yes.

105
00:06:34,644 --> 00:06:35,478
One more thing.

106
00:06:36,437 --> 00:06:40,525
You don't have to tell me what Inmate 6238
thinks from now on. I don't trust him.

107
00:06:46,364 --> 00:06:47,865
Si-young, how did it go?

108
00:06:47,949 --> 00:06:49,367
He's still being tested.

109
00:06:49,450 --> 00:06:52,662
My goodness. Why did this happen
right before his release?

110
00:06:53,579 --> 00:06:54,455
Will he recover?

111
00:06:54,539 --> 00:06:56,207
We're suspecting a genetic disorder.

112
00:06:56,290 --> 00:07:00,336
We need his family history to see
if anyone else has had the same symptoms.

113
00:07:00,962 --> 00:07:02,630
Did you hear that? Find that out.

114
00:07:02,713 --> 00:07:04,674
Tell his family to come
as soon as they can.

115
00:07:04,757 --> 00:07:05,591
-Yes.
-Yes.

116
00:07:09,053 --> 00:07:13,141
By the way, are you okay
with missing your flight?

117
00:07:14,183 --> 00:07:16,018
You're staying, right?

118
00:07:16,102 --> 00:07:17,937
I didn't say I'd stay.

119
00:07:18,020 --> 00:07:19,981
What? No?

120
00:07:20,064 --> 00:07:22,608
I'll leave as soon
as he's diagnosed and stable again.

121
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:24,569
I can always find another flight.

122
00:07:26,446 --> 00:07:28,614
Inmate 6238 made a good call.

123
00:07:29,282 --> 00:07:30,324
What's with him?

124
00:07:30,408 --> 00:07:33,369
He also said Si-young
was the one who will save the patient.

125
00:07:36,330 --> 00:07:37,874
I'll be released next week.

126
00:07:37,957 --> 00:07:40,793
I'll go to a big hospital then
like you told me to.

127
00:07:40,877 --> 00:07:42,753
What if you die before your release?

128
00:07:56,225 --> 00:07:57,810
Yo-han, it's today.

129
00:07:58,311 --> 00:07:59,437
D-day.

130
00:08:06,694 --> 00:08:08,404
Are you not done yet? Hurry up.

131
00:08:41,312 --> 00:08:44,357
-Did you get your certificate?
-Of course.

132
00:08:46,025 --> 00:08:46,901
Here it is.

133
00:08:46,984 --> 00:08:50,196
1ST CLASS BARISTA CERTIFICATE

134
00:08:50,279 --> 00:08:52,907
Your vocational training here paid off.

135
00:08:52,990 --> 00:08:55,660
You could start working
as a barista as soon as you're out.

136
00:08:56,953 --> 00:09:00,164
Yo-han, when I get a job,
come taste my coffee.

137
00:09:00,706 --> 00:09:02,959
I'll brew a really good cup
of coffee for you.

138
00:09:09,799 --> 00:09:10,758
All right.

139
00:09:12,093 --> 00:09:12,927
Here you go.

140
00:09:24,772 --> 00:09:26,607
Coffee tastes best when it's piping hot.

141
00:09:27,441 --> 00:09:29,026
I can't drink something too hot.

142
00:09:29,110 --> 00:09:30,361
My goodness.

143
00:09:30,861 --> 00:09:32,905
Sometimes, you're just like a little kid.

144
00:09:32,989 --> 00:09:35,116
You can't eat hot and spicy foods.

145
00:09:43,624 --> 00:09:45,418
-It's perfect.
-I'm so relieved.

146
00:09:46,711 --> 00:09:49,755
By the way, why are you so nice to me?

147
00:09:52,425 --> 00:09:55,386
You were the first person.

148
00:09:56,387 --> 00:09:58,139
"First"? What do you mean?

149
00:09:58,848 --> 00:10:00,308
You were the first person

150
00:10:01,017 --> 00:10:04,478
who didn't think
I was only pretending to be sick.

151
00:10:05,521 --> 00:10:07,481
My mom was sick all the time too.

152
00:10:08,357 --> 00:10:12,361
She was always laughed at by my dad
for pretending to be sick

153
00:10:13,237 --> 00:10:14,822
until she passed away.

154
00:10:18,367 --> 00:10:21,120
No refills. Please leave now, sir.

155
00:10:21,746 --> 00:10:24,332
Can I make another phone call?

156
00:10:25,583 --> 00:10:29,420
By the way, the doctor earlier
seemed to know Inmate 6238.

157
00:10:30,379 --> 00:10:31,839
Do you mean Dr. Lee Yoo-joon?

158
00:10:32,423 --> 00:10:35,509
He's the one who usually treats
our patients.

159
00:10:36,052 --> 00:10:39,513
He made a couple of misdiagnoses,

160
00:10:39,597 --> 00:10:41,641
and Inmate 6238 corrected them.

161
00:10:41,724 --> 00:10:43,476
It totally hurt his pride.

162
00:10:44,060 --> 00:10:46,854
I knew it. He seemed to despise him.

163
00:10:46,937 --> 00:10:50,316
Inmate 6238 is his biggest enemy
even though they haven't even met.

164
00:10:57,406 --> 00:10:58,407
Yes?

165
00:11:00,368 --> 00:11:01,494
Inmate 6238?

166
00:11:02,662 --> 00:11:03,579
Let me talk to him.

167
00:11:05,373 --> 00:11:09,543
Yes. They're doing a kidney biopsy.

168
00:11:09,627 --> 00:11:12,588
They're still finding out
about his family history.

169
00:11:13,172 --> 00:11:14,507
All right.

170
00:11:17,551 --> 00:11:19,220
What? Did he just hang up?

171
00:11:19,303 --> 00:11:21,472
Why? Do you have something to tell him?

172
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:23,641
Didn't he ask for me?

173
00:11:23,724 --> 00:11:24,558
No.

174
00:11:26,352 --> 00:11:28,604
Uncle, can you call him back?

175
00:11:29,605 --> 00:11:30,523
Inmate 6238.

176
00:11:31,607 --> 00:11:32,733
There's a call for you.

177
00:11:38,948 --> 00:11:41,409
-Hello?
-They're doing a kidney biopsy.

178
00:11:41,492 --> 00:11:43,369
-I heard.
-Exactly.

179
00:11:43,911 --> 00:11:45,871
-What?
-You asked me in the first place.

180
00:11:46,705 --> 00:11:48,290
Why did you only talk to my uncle?

181
00:11:49,250 --> 00:11:50,376
Are the results out yet?

182
00:11:51,001 --> 00:11:53,003
-Of course not.
-Let's talk when they're out.

183
00:11:53,087 --> 00:11:54,130
Hang on.

184
00:11:57,299 --> 00:11:59,468
What am I supposed to do?

185
00:11:59,552 --> 00:12:01,262
-What do you mean?
-You said

186
00:12:01,804 --> 00:12:06,350
if I followed the patient to the hospital,
you'd tell me how to save him.

187
00:12:06,434 --> 00:12:10,438
Did you tell the doctor on duty
to test him for Fabry disease?

188
00:12:10,521 --> 00:12:11,439
You told me to.

189
00:12:11,522 --> 00:12:13,023
That's how you save the patient.

190
00:12:13,107 --> 00:12:14,859
Can you talk so that I can understand?

191
00:12:14,942 --> 00:12:16,861
If prison officers told the doctor

192
00:12:16,944 --> 00:12:20,072
the patient might have Fabry disease,
would he have believed them?

193
00:12:21,198 --> 00:12:22,658
They would have wasted time

194
00:12:22,741 --> 00:12:25,369
doing all kinds of tests on him
while the patient became worse.

195
00:12:25,453 --> 00:12:26,370
Are you saying…

196
00:12:28,414 --> 00:12:29,790
you just borrowed my mouth?

197
00:12:30,916 --> 00:12:31,750
This time,

198
00:12:32,418 --> 00:12:33,919
can I borrow your hands?

199
00:12:36,005 --> 00:12:36,839
My hands?

200
00:12:37,548 --> 00:12:40,926
Now, you need to find ERT,
which is the treatment for Fabry disease.

201
00:12:41,010 --> 00:12:43,304
If you try to receive it
through a pharmaceutical company,

202
00:12:43,387 --> 00:12:44,555
it'll take over a week.

203
00:12:44,638 --> 00:12:47,183
The fastest way to get it
is to look for a hospital

204
00:12:47,266 --> 00:12:48,934
that has a Nephrology Department.

205
00:12:49,018 --> 00:12:51,145
And if they have any patients
with Fabry disease,

206
00:12:51,228 --> 00:12:52,980
you can borrow the ERT from them.

207
00:12:54,190 --> 00:12:55,399
You don't have any?

208
00:12:55,483 --> 00:12:57,610
Hello, I'd like to talk
to the Nephrology Department.

209
00:12:57,693 --> 00:12:59,445
I'm looking for ERT.

210
00:13:14,001 --> 00:13:16,420
Can I talk to the Nephrology Department?

211
00:13:18,631 --> 00:13:20,674
Dr. Lee!

212
00:13:22,343 --> 00:13:24,720
-I found ERT.
-Where?

213
00:13:24,803 --> 00:13:26,764
A university hospital
40 minutes away from here.

214
00:13:26,847 --> 00:13:28,766
-We can borrow it if we go now.
-Did they agree?

215
00:13:28,849 --> 00:13:31,936
I promised to return it
if it isn't Fabry disease

216
00:13:32,019 --> 00:13:33,437
because I know it's very expensive.

217
00:13:34,146 --> 00:13:35,981
But we don't even have
a definite diagnosis yet.

218
00:13:36,065 --> 00:13:37,650
So I mentioned your name.

219
00:13:38,692 --> 00:13:40,903
-What?
-You have a great reputation.

220
00:13:40,986 --> 00:13:43,781
I heard you are
the most competent fellow here.

221
00:13:45,616 --> 00:13:48,327
Well, I'm not exactly that competent.

222
00:13:48,410 --> 00:13:51,038
This is a small neighborhood,
so word spreads fast.

223
00:13:51,121 --> 00:13:54,833
And the elders tend to always ask for me.

224
00:13:58,963 --> 00:14:01,006
Can you chart it and send it here?

225
00:14:04,552 --> 00:14:06,512
Do you really think it's Fabry disease?

226
00:14:06,595 --> 00:14:10,099
You told me earlier
that it's a 0.00001 percent probability.

227
00:14:10,891 --> 00:14:13,811
I like that possibility.

228
00:14:16,146 --> 00:14:17,147
I'll be back.

229
00:14:21,151 --> 00:14:22,987
THANK YOU, DR. LEE!

230
00:14:24,989 --> 00:14:26,073
My gosh.

231
00:14:36,417 --> 00:14:37,918
-I'll be right back.
-Okay.

232
00:14:45,926 --> 00:14:47,469
EMERGENCY MEDICAL CENTER

233
00:14:47,553 --> 00:14:51,015
Tae-kyung, what did I tell you? I told you
I had a good feeling about this.

234
00:14:52,224 --> 00:14:54,268
That patient that got taken
to the hospital earlier,

235
00:14:54,351 --> 00:14:56,937
-do they know what his illness is?
-No, not yet.

236
00:14:57,021 --> 00:14:59,148
But they already have a guess
as to what it could be,

237
00:14:59,231 --> 00:15:01,567
and Si-young's trying her best
to find the cure.

238
00:15:01,650 --> 00:15:04,820
That means he didn't even get diagnosed
yet, and he's in a bad condition.

239
00:15:04,904 --> 00:15:07,489
Well, yes.

240
00:15:10,367 --> 00:15:11,619
Let Si-young go.

241
00:15:11,702 --> 00:15:12,536
What?

242
00:15:14,455 --> 00:15:15,289
Why?

243
00:15:15,372 --> 00:15:16,999
It's her first patient after the accident.

244
00:15:17,082 --> 00:15:18,042
If something goes wrong,

245
00:15:20,461 --> 00:15:22,379
she won't be able to handle it.

246
00:15:38,395 --> 00:15:40,105
Where can you buy those things?

247
00:15:40,606 --> 00:15:42,274
I'll be released next week.

248
00:15:42,775 --> 00:15:46,153
I'm meeting my sister after years.
I'd love to get a bracelet for her.

249
00:15:54,954 --> 00:15:56,413
-Uncle.
-Hey.

250
00:16:01,460 --> 00:16:02,461
What's wrong?

251
00:16:03,671 --> 00:16:04,546
Nothing.

252
00:16:05,047 --> 00:16:07,883
It's been a while
since I've seen you so excited.

253
00:16:08,634 --> 00:16:09,551
Let's go.

254
00:16:13,722 --> 00:16:15,099
Si-young.

255
00:16:15,641 --> 00:16:18,644
How about you take your hands off this
after you give them that cure?

256
00:16:19,311 --> 00:16:21,897
I'll… I'll take you home.

257
00:16:23,691 --> 00:16:24,775
Why all of a sudden?

258
00:16:25,776 --> 00:16:27,194
You wanted me to stay.

259
