-He's being transferred.

524
00:40:21,710 --> 00:40:23,754
Well, that was…

525
00:40:25,297 --> 00:40:27,550
His father was so adamant.

526
00:40:29,552 --> 00:40:31,220
There's nothing I can do now.

527
00:40:31,303 --> 00:40:32,596
You tried hard.

528
00:40:33,389 --> 00:40:35,057
Ever since last night.

529
00:40:35,141 --> 00:40:36,600
No.

530
00:40:37,226 --> 00:40:39,937
"Need to visit Nephrology
at a tertiary hospital. Urgent."

531
00:40:40,020 --> 00:40:41,981
If only I'd listened.

532
00:40:42,648 --> 00:40:44,358
If only I'd sent him to a hospital.

533
00:40:52,032 --> 00:40:52,867
Hi.

534
00:40:57,830 --> 00:40:59,623
-A transfer?
-Yes.

535
00:41:00,291 --> 00:41:03,002
-He'll be transferred.
-It'll be a mess if he's transferred.

536
00:41:03,085 --> 00:41:04,336
They'll have to start over.

537
00:41:04,837 --> 00:41:06,172
There's nothing we can do.

538
00:41:06,797 --> 00:41:08,382
They can't do anything here.

539
00:41:18,934 --> 00:41:19,768
You have the cure.

540
00:41:19,852 --> 00:41:21,103
The cure?

541
00:41:22,396 --> 00:41:24,023
Si-young got some yesterday.

542
00:41:24,106 --> 00:41:25,399
Put it in his room.

543
00:41:26,317 --> 00:41:27,693
Put it next to the bed.

544
00:41:27,776 --> 00:41:29,028
I'll come over.

545
00:41:29,111 --> 00:41:31,363
What? Hello? Hello? Inmate 6238.

546
00:41:33,032 --> 00:41:33,949
What was that about?

547
00:41:35,117 --> 00:41:36,035
What did he say?

548
00:41:36,118 --> 00:41:39,413
He wants you to put the cure by the bed.

549
00:41:40,206 --> 00:41:41,040
The cure?

550
00:41:43,209 --> 00:41:44,293
Yes, the cure.

551
00:41:45,711 --> 00:41:46,587
Thanks, Uncle.

552
00:41:46,670 --> 00:41:47,838
Thank you.

553
00:41:49,381 --> 00:41:51,091
Si-young.

554
00:41:59,183 --> 00:42:00,392
Dr. Lee.

555
00:42:03,979 --> 00:42:05,231
Do you have more to say?

556
00:42:06,357 --> 00:42:07,816
Just prepare the ERT medicine.

557
00:42:09,193 --> 00:42:11,695
The hospital he'll be transferred to
could need it.

558
00:42:14,406 --> 00:42:16,200
It takes a while to procure.

559
00:42:16,283 --> 00:42:17,993
Just in case.

560
00:42:18,744 --> 00:42:21,080
That's why we went
to such lengths to get it.

561
00:42:33,175 --> 00:42:34,218
It's the ERT medicine.

562
00:42:35,052 --> 00:42:36,053
Take it, just in case.

563
00:42:36,136 --> 00:42:38,389
Pass it on to the hospital
he'll be transferred to.

564
00:42:38,472 --> 00:42:40,349
-Okay. I'll do that.
-No.

565
00:42:41,976 --> 00:42:44,645
He has to be injected right now.

566
00:42:45,271 --> 00:42:46,981
The patient has Fabry disease.

567
00:42:47,064 --> 00:42:48,941
How many times must I say
he had no zebra bodies?

568
00:42:49,024 --> 00:42:51,360
It's rare, but depending
on where the tissue was from,

569
00:42:51,443 --> 00:42:53,070
zebra bodies might be absent.

570
00:42:53,153 --> 00:42:54,780
Said who? Inmate 6238?

571
00:42:55,698 --> 00:42:57,324
Are you crazy?

572
00:42:57,408 --> 00:43:01,370
You believe it's Fabry disease because
a doctor who lost his license said so?

573
00:43:01,453 --> 00:43:02,496
Get out.

574
00:43:02,580 --> 00:43:04,039
Get out right now.

575
00:43:13,173 --> 00:43:15,259
Dr. Lee Yoo-joon
whom I've heard so much about?

576
00:43:15,843 --> 00:43:16,760
Who are you?

577
00:43:16,844 --> 00:43:18,012
Nice to meet you.

578
00:43:18,095 --> 00:43:19,305
I'm Inmate 6238.

579
00:43:23,225 --> 00:43:24,226
Excuse me.

580
00:43:27,771 --> 00:43:29,982
Wait. How did you get here?

581
00:43:31,108 --> 00:43:32,318
Inmate 6238.

582
00:43:33,652 --> 00:43:36,530
As of noon today, he's a free man.

583
00:43:40,868 --> 00:43:42,911
A few years ago, a patient came

584
00:43:42,995 --> 00:43:46,290
to Myeongwon University Hospital's
Nephrology Department.

585
00:43:47,124 --> 00:43:49,960
After suffering from albuminuria,
she deteriorated rapidly

586
00:43:50,628 --> 00:43:52,379
and required dialysis.

587
00:43:53,172 --> 00:43:54,548
Her kidney biopsy

588
00:43:55,174 --> 00:43:57,176
showed she had FSGS.

589
00:43:58,886 --> 00:44:02,765
That's exactly what
Dr. Lee diagnosed Jung-bo with.

590
00:44:05,267 --> 00:44:08,604
The patient's sister
offered to give her a kidney,

591
00:44:08,687 --> 00:44:10,898
but guess what her biopsy showed?

592
00:44:10,981 --> 00:44:14,026
Thick and clear zebra bodies.

593
00:44:14,109 --> 00:44:15,611
She had Fabry disease.

594
00:44:16,570 --> 00:44:17,404
Did she?

595
00:44:18,238 --> 00:44:20,491
-Then why did her sister--
-Not show the same?

596
00:44:21,367 --> 00:44:22,618
It's not that she didn't.

597
00:44:23,619 --> 00:44:25,746
They were obscured by the many dead cells.

598
00:44:25,829 --> 00:44:26,997
Just like Jung-bo's case.

599
00:44:28,624 --> 00:44:30,292
You can't transfer him now.

600
00:44:30,376 --> 00:44:32,002
While they search for a diagnosis,

601
00:44:32,086 --> 00:44:33,962
he could deteriorate beyond help.

602
00:44:34,046 --> 00:44:35,255
He must be treated here.

603
00:44:35,339 --> 00:44:37,508
Treatment comes
after a definite diagnosis.

604
00:44:38,092 --> 00:44:39,510
A definite diagnosis?

605
00:44:40,886 --> 00:44:42,930
What's the prevalence rate
of Fabry disease?

606
00:44:43,013 --> 00:44:43,931
You know what it is.

607
00:44:44,723 --> 00:44:46,475
One out of 117,000.

608
00:44:47,101 --> 00:44:48,936
-It's very rare.
-Not at all.

609
00:44:49,019 --> 00:44:51,605
If you include all the people
who couldn't get a diagnosis

610
00:44:51,688 --> 00:44:54,650
despite visiting many hospitals,
resorted to alternative medicine,

611
00:44:54,733 --> 00:44:56,902
lost their savings, and died,
Fabry patients…

612
00:44:58,612 --> 00:45:00,322
are more numerous than you think.

613
00:45:01,281 --> 00:45:05,869
They can live if they're just diagnosed,
but many people died because they weren't.

614
00:45:05,953 --> 00:45:07,996
We don't have that diagnosis yet.

615
00:45:08,705 --> 00:45:12,042
You want to inject an expensive cure
to an ambiguous case?

616
00:45:12,126 --> 00:45:14,169
Why should I take such a risk?

617
00:45:14,253 --> 00:45:16,046
It's the patient who's taking the risk.

618
00:45:17,047 --> 00:45:18,424
You flooded him with steroids.

619
00:45:18,924 --> 00:45:21,385
If his kidneys fail and
can't even withstand transplant surgery,

620
00:45:21,468 --> 00:45:23,470
-who'll take the blame?
-How dare you threaten me?

621
00:45:23,554 --> 00:45:26,849
This is a warning, not a threat.
From the patient's whole body.

622
00:45:26,932 --> 00:45:28,225
He's my patient!

623
00:45:32,604 --> 00:45:35,649
You might have been
a famous professor of medicine,

624
00:45:35,732 --> 00:45:37,276
but he's my patient right now.

625
00:45:38,694 --> 00:45:39,987
So stay out of it.

626
00:45:43,407 --> 00:45:45,826
Are you really sure
it's not Fabry disease?

627
00:45:49,830 --> 00:45:51,915
It's true that you're his doctor.

628
00:45:52,833 --> 00:45:55,669
But I followed his condition for a year.

629
00:45:58,714 --> 00:46:00,090
In prison.

630
00:46:01,717 --> 00:46:03,260
I'm not like you.

631
00:46:03,969 --> 00:46:06,138
I won't risk my license like that.

632
00:46:13,228 --> 00:46:14,354
Have him transferred.

633
00:46:26,909 --> 00:46:27,910
What are you doing?

634
00:46:34,333 --> 00:46:35,584
You're not a doctor!

635
00:46:41,089 --> 00:46:43,675
Don't you know it's illegal
to treat without a license?

636
00:46:56,522 --> 00:46:58,941
Dr. Kang, are you a doctor?

637
00:47:13,747 --> 00:47:14,623
Yes.

638
00:47:15,916 --> 00:47:17,084
I'm a doctor.

639
00:47:45,946 --> 00:47:47,030
What on earth…

640
00:47:49,700 --> 00:47:51,827
-I'll take responsibility.
-Will you?

641
00:47:51,910 --> 00:47:52,869
How?

642
00:47:53,745 --> 00:47:56,582
-Treating when you aren't staff…
-I'll accept any punishment.

643
00:47:56,665 --> 00:47:58,709
But if we don't do anything,

644
00:47:59,376 --> 00:48:00,836
the patient continues to suffer.

645
00:48:01,670 --> 00:48:02,921
Not because of the illness,

646
00:48:05,924 --> 00:48:07,384
but because the doctor

647
00:48:08,677 --> 00:48:09,886
did nothing.

648
00:48:17,102 --> 00:48:17,936
Dr. Lee.

649
00:48:19,229 --> 00:48:20,355
His brother's here.

650
00:48:21,356 --> 00:48:22,649
-Jung-min.
-Father.

651
00:48:24,234 --> 00:48:25,068
Jung-bo.

652
00:48:26,653 --> 00:48:29,406
Why are you sick too?

653
00:48:32,409 --> 00:48:33,827
I'm sorry, Father.

654
00:48:34,870 --> 00:48:36,747
Why are you sorry?

655
00:48:37,414 --> 00:48:39,249
It's all my fault.

656
00:48:39,333 --> 00:48:41,293
He's on dialysis.

657
00:48:42,878 --> 00:48:45,922
Doctor, please save my sons.

658
00:48:46,715 --> 00:48:49,051
I'm not afraid of losing them.

659
00:48:49,134 --> 00:48:53,221
I'm more afraid that they'll die,
like their mom and sister,

660
00:48:53,305 --> 00:48:54,723
not knowing what they have.

661
00:48:55,849 --> 00:48:59,936
What kind of illness is it
that's so cruel to us?

662
00:49:00,437 --> 00:49:02,814
Please save my sons.

663
00:49:05,484 --> 00:49:07,152
Do a kidney biopsy on the brother.

664
00:49:08,320 --> 00:49:09,946
You'll see it right away.

665
00:49:53,115 --> 00:49:54,366
I see it.

666
00:49:54,449 --> 00:49:55,450
He'll live.

667
00:49:57,494 --> 00:49:59,788
You saved him, Dr. Kang. And…

668
00:50:16,096 --> 00:50:17,097
Dr. Lee.

669
00:50:18,390 --> 00:50:19,224
What is it?

670
00:50:20,809 --> 00:50:22,769
It's definitely Fabry disease.

671
00:50:23,395 --> 00:50:24,646
Then, will he get better?

672
00:50:24,730 --> 00:50:29,025
Yes. Both of your sons can be treated.

673
00:50:31,153 --> 00:50:33,530
Thank you, doctor. Thank you.

674
00:50:34,948 --> 00:50:37,492
Dr. Lee, thank you.

675
00:50:37,576 --> 00:50:38,577
Well…

676
00:50:40,287 --> 00:50:43,248
Si-young, thank you. You did well.

677
00:50:49,296 --> 00:50:50,422
Inmate 6238?

678
00:50:50,922 --> 00:50:53,592
Oh, we shouldn't call him that anymore.
He's Cha Yo-han now.

679
00:50:54,926 --> 00:50:55,844
He just left.

680
00:50:57,596 --> 00:50:59,723
He left? Where did he go?

681
00:50:59,806 --> 00:51:01,975
Anywhere, I guess. He's free now.

682
00:52:07,332 --> 00:52:08,750
Welcome back, Professor Cha.

683
00:52:15,924 --> 00:52:17,300
Wait!

684
00:52:18,426 --> 00:52:19,761
Wait!

685
00:52:19,845 --> 00:52:21,179
Dr. Cha!

686
00:52:22,180 --> 00:52:23,139
Cha Yo-han!

687
00:52:23,932 --> 00:52:25,225
Dr. Cha!

688
00:52:28,311 --> 00:52:29,563
Dr. Cha!

689
00:52:30,564 --> 00:52:31,815
Dr. Cha!

690
00:52:51,835 --> 00:52:52,669
Can I…

691
00:52:53,920 --> 00:52:55,338
go back?

692
00:52:57,215 --> 00:52:58,842
Can I do well?

693
00:53:03,763 --> 00:53:06,349
HANSE MEDICAL CENTER

694
00:53:06,433 --> 00:53:09,102
I have an announcement to make.

695
00:53:10,228 --> 00:53:12,439
It is about Kang Si-young,
a second-year resident

696
00:53:12,522 --> 00:53:14,024
of the Anesthesiology Department.

697
00:53:18,153 --> 00:53:19,195
I'm considering

698
00:53:20,113 --> 00:53:22,032
accepting her back.

699
00:53:28,747 --> 00:53:31,875
She's been undergoing psychotherapy.

700
00:53:31,958 --> 00:53:34,711
Recently, it was diagnosed
that she doesn't have PTSD.

701
00:53:34,794 --> 00:53:37,547
She completed
the training process successfully

702
00:53:37,631 --> 00:53:41,301
and always received
excellent resident evaluations.

703
00:53:41,384 --> 00:53:42,385
However,

704
00:53:43,178 --> 00:53:45,680
we can't be sure
if she's ready to treat patients

705
00:53:46,306 --> 00:53:48,099
without being affected by the incident.

706
00:53:48,183 --> 00:53:51,144
It was just an accident.

707
00:53:51,227 --> 00:53:54,147
I guess how long it takes
to recover from an accident

708
00:53:54,230 --> 00:53:55,482
depends on the person.

709
00:53:56,191 --> 00:53:57,359
Yes, it was an accident.

710
00:53:57,442 --> 00:54:01,196
Still, there were other things
she needed to work on even before that.

711
00:54:02,530 --> 00:54:03,615
Like what?

712
00:54:03,698 --> 00:54:07,118
Excessive empathy
with her patients, of course.

713
00:54:08,286 --> 00:54:11,831
Yes. From the first year,
her examinations took too long.

714
00:54:11,915 --> 00:54:15,043
She was even ordered not to talk
to her patients for longer than a minute.

715
00:54:15,126 --> 00:54:16,503
That could be

716
00:54:16,586 --> 00:54:17,754
a strength too.

717
00:54:18,672 --> 00:54:22,968
Residents often fail to understand
their patients well enough.

718
00:54:23,051 --> 00:54:25,387
But her excessive empathy

719
00:54:25,470 --> 00:54:28,264
often clouded her judgment as a doctor.

720
00:54:28,890 --> 00:54:30,934
Who knows if the incident happened
because--

721
00:54:56,376 --> 00:54:58,211
Aren't you sick of chicken breast yet?

722
00:54:58,294 --> 00:55:00,755
Why does it have so much protein anyway?

723
00:55:10,473 --> 00:55:12,976
I'm sorry.

724
00:55:14,561 --> 00:55:16,438
I caused you all trouble
by quitting so suddenly.

725
00:55:16,521 --> 00:55:20,025
And now, I shamelessly came back.
I'm really sorry.

726
00:55:28,074 --> 00:55:29,534
Nice to see you again, Si-young.

727
00:55:32,078 --> 00:55:33,621
Nice to see you too, Jun.

728
00:55:36,750 --> 00:55:38,168
"Nice to see you again,

729
00:55:39,127 --> 00:55:40,045
Dr. Heo."

730
00:55:41,546 --> 00:55:44,466
You're only a second-year.
We're not in the same year anymore.

731
00:55:44,549 --> 00:55:45,550
I'm a fourth-year.

732
00:55:47,343 --> 00:55:48,636
Show some respect.

733
00:55:49,262 --> 00:55:50,263
Yes.

734
00:55:51,473 --> 00:55:53,933
Everyone, we're late. Let's go.

735
00:55:54,017 --> 00:55:56,144
Stop eating chicken breast.

736
00:56:05,153 --> 00:56:07,072
-Mi-rae.
-Don't call me by my first name.

737
00:56:07,155 --> 00:56:08,531
I'm a third-year now.

738
00:56:09,949 --> 00:56:11,159
I had…

739
00:56:13,244 --> 00:56:14,662
two choices.

740
00:56:16,414 --> 00:56:19,084
I could either run away or come back here.

741
00:56:19,167 --> 00:56:20,293
I saw it.

742
00:56:20,960 --> 00:56:22,504
Your one-way ticket to Madagascar.

743
00:56:24,464 --> 00:56:27,467
Why didn't you just go?
You're not going to last long anyway.

744
00:56:46,611 --> 00:56:47,737
KANG SI-YOUNG

745
00:56:56,830 --> 00:56:59,499
Dr. Kang, are you a doctor?

746
00:57:00,375 --> 00:57:02,877
Yes, I'm a doctor.

747
00:57:11,553 --> 00:57:15,056
ANESTHESIOLOGY

748
00:57:38,079 --> 00:57:39,873
It's my first day back at the hospital.

749
00:57:40,540 --> 00:57:42,250
I'm sorry it took so long.

750
00:57:43,126 --> 00:57:44,377
I won't let you down.

751
00:57:49,090 --> 00:57:50,091
Excuse me.

752
00:58:10,153 --> 00:58:14,282
CHA YO-HAN

753
00:59:11,130 --> 00:59:12,131
We meet again.

754
00:59:16,177 --> 00:59:19,138
SPECIAL THANKS TO JEON NO-MIN
AND JUNG IN-GI FOR THEIR CAMEO PARTS

755
00:59:32,735 --> 00:59:34,487
This person is a murderer.

756
00:59:34,571 --> 00:59:35,780
He is a doctor.

757
00:59:35,863 --> 00:59:37,949
He killed a person.

758
00:59:41,160 --> 00:59:42,453
Male, 38 years old.

759
00:59:43,246 --> 00:59:45,790
This patient had an emergency canthotomy
two days ago.

760
00:59:45,873 --> 00:59:48,167
The patient refused
any treatment or tests.

761
00:59:48,251 --> 00:59:49,627
He wanted Dr. Cha to be prohibited

762
00:59:49,711 --> 00:59:52,255
-from approaching him.
-Do you want to learn from me?

763
00:59:52,338 --> 00:59:54,340
-But don't learn these things.
-We say no!

764
00:59:54,424 --> 00:59:57,010
What is going on?

765
00:59:57,093 --> 00:59:58,303
Is Cha Yo-han in?

766
00:59:58,386 --> 01:00:01,889
I haven't seen Professor Cha
in three years.

